<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-719-876  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 719 876.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  Sept 14 1989 v15 n19 p8(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>; IBM tests chip for high-speed optical link in computers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Powell, Doug.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>An experimental chip set being developed by IBM Corp holds thepotential of transmitting and receiving data over fiber opticlines at a speed of a billion bits per second (1G-bps).andP;  IBM hasdeveloped quarter-inch receptor chips capable of holding 50 timesthe optical and electronic data capable of being assembled on achip using optoelectronic receiving and processing.andP;  The receiverchip has over 8,000 transistors and can handle byte-wide streamsof data.andP;  These streams are converted into a high-speed streamdriven by a gallium arsenide injection laser.andP;  Converted into aform of light, the data is then sent through optical fiber andconverted back into a digital stream.andP;  IBM's announcementindicates that the high-speed transmission and reduced costs ofthis chip set will make more reliable connection across a range ofcomputers possible.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Fiber OpticsProduct DevelopmentMicroprocessorsTransmission SpeedInformation Storage and RetrievalChip Sets.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>